revision.text:
{{Infobox magazine | title = al-Kātib al-miṣrī | logo = | logo_size = 180px | image_file = Titelblatt al-katib al-misri Jahrgang 1 Nummer 1 1945.jpg | image_size = 180px | image_alt = | image_caption = | editor = Taha Hussein | editor_title = | previous_editor = | staff_writer = | photographer = | category = Literature, Arts, Science | frequency = | format = | circulation = | publisher = | paid_circulation = | unpaid_circulation = | circulation_year = | total_circulation = | founder = | founded = 1945 | firstdate = | finaldate = | finalnumber = | company = | country = Egypt | based = Cairo | language = Arabic | issn = | oclc = }}
The Egyptian journal al-Katib al-misri ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]: الكاتب المصري; [[Deutsche Morgenländische Gesellschaft|DMG]]: al-Kātib al-miṣrī; [[English language|English]]: "The Egyptian Writer") was published in Cairo monthly from 1945-1948. It was founded originally by the Egyptian Press and Publishing House owned by the Jewish al-Harari family who entrusted [[Taha Hussein]] (1889-1973) with the management.<ref>Mohamed El-Bendary (2010): The Egyptian Press and Coverage of Local and International Events. US Lexington Books, Lanham, p. 3.</ref> The magazine was published in total in 32 issues and was available in numerous Arab metropolises.<ref>May Hawas (2018): Taha Hussein and the Case for World Literature. In: Comparative Literature Studies. Vol. 55, Issue 1, p. 66–92.</ref>
The focus of the journal was the publication of international literature and literary criticism, which were translated into Arabic and so helped to reach a broader readership. Both Arabic and non-Arabic art, literature and science were encouraged and a dialogue between Arabic and other languages should be established.<ref>May Hawas (2018): Taha Hussein and the Case for World Literature. In: Comparative Literature Studies. Vol. 55, Issue 1, p. 66–92.</ref>
As one of the first post-war magazines, al-Kātib al-miṣrī also aimed to make its vision of the enlightenment accessible to all and to promote mutual cultural exchange.<ref>Jens Hanssen and Max Weiss (2018): Arabic Thought against the Authoritarian Age: Towards an Intellectual History of the Present. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, p. 45.</ref> "Literature should be lifted above all conflicts existing world-wide."<ref>al-Kātib al-Miṣrī (1945), Vol. 1, Issue 1-3.</ref>
Arabic translations among others, of works by [[Antoine de Saint-Exupéry]] or [[Jean-Paul Satre]],<ref>Jens Hanssen and Max Weiss (2018): Arabic Thought against the Authoritarian Age: Towards an Intellectual History of the Present. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, p. 46.</ref> were published, texts of promising new Arab authors<ref>Christopher Dwight Micklethwait (2010): Faits Divers: National Culture and Modernism in Third World Literary Magazines. Diss. The University of Texas at Austin, p. 175.</ref> as well as literary criticism, which also offered an introduction by Western authors such as [[James Joyce]] or [[Franz Kafka]].<ref>Elisabeth Kendall (2006): Literature, Journalism and the Avant-Garde: Intersection in Egypt. Taylor and Francis Routledge, New York/ London, p. 55 ff.</ref>
Moreover two other sections also discussed in detail the contents and orientations of Arabic and European periodicals of the time.<ref>Christopher Dwight Micklethwait (2010): Faits Divers: National Culture and Modernism in Third World Literary Magazines. Diss. The University of Texas at Austin, p. 184.</ref> In 1948, the publication of the magazine was stopped, whereby it is not clear whether this was spontaneous or under governmental pressure.<ref>Elisabeth Kendall (2006): Literature, Journalism and the Avant-Garde: Intersection in Egypt. Taylor and Francis Routledge, New York/ London, p. 56.</ref>
