{{Infobox person | name = Meyrav Wurmser | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- maiden name --> | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Birth-date and age|birth date†}} --> | birth_place = Israel | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date†|birth date†}} --> | death_place = | nationality = Israel, American | other_names = Meirav Wurmser | occupation = | years_active = | residence = [[Maryland]] | known_for = Cofounder of [[Middle East Media Research Institute]] (MEMRI) | spouse =[[David Wurmser]] | notable_works = }} '''Meyrav Wurmser''' is an [[Israelis|Israeli]]- [[United States|American]] [[neoconservative]] political executive. She is married to [[Swiss people|Swiss]]-[[United States|American]] [[David Wurmser]], former [[Middle East]] Adviser to [[US Vice President]] [[Dick Cheney]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/panorama/3034221.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Programmes - Panorama - Meyrav Wurmser|work=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref> She was formerly a [[Senior Fellow]] at the [[United States|US]] [[think tank]], the [[Hudson Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hudson.org/experts/450-meyrav-wurmser|title=Experts - Meyrav Wurmser - Hudson Institute|work=hudson.org|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref>
From 1998 to 2001, Wurmser was a co-founder and Executive Director [[Middle East Media Research Institute]] (MEMRI)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3340750,00.html|title=Neocons: We expected Israel to attack Syria|work=ynet|accessdate=13 June 2015}}</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2012/03/08/should-israel-accept-a-nuclear-ban/a-linchpin-of-security-cannot-be-surrendered</ref> together with [[Yigal Carmon]].
{{citation needed span|text= Wurmser wrote her Ph.D. thesis on [[Revisionist Zionism]] behind the [[Herut]] and [[Likud]] parties, and received her doctorate in political science at [[George Washington University]] in 1998.|date=June 2015}} {{citation needed span|text=She went on to teach political science at [[Johns Hopkins University]] and the [[US Naval Academy]].|date=June 2015}}
In 1996, Wurmser participated in a study that led to the report, ''[[A Clean Break: A New Strategy for Securing the Realm]]'', a paper prepared for the [[Likud]] party leader and then incoming [[Israel]]i Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], and suggested a new approach to solving Israel's security problems in the Middle East with an emphasis on "Western values" and the abandonment of traditional "[[land for peace]]" negotiations with the [[Palestinians]].<ref>Daily Telegraph, London, 5 October 2007.</ref> Other study participants included such notable [[neoconservative]]s as [[Richard Perle]], [[David Wurmser]], and [[Douglas Feith]].
In 2008, Wurmser was listed as a member of the board of advisors of the [[Endowment for Middle East Truth]], a group which was involved in the distribution of 28 million DVDs of the film [[Obsession: Radical Islam's War Against the West]] in [[swing state]]s prior to the [[United States presidential election, 2008|2008 US Presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=43983 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-10-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015014835/http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=43983 |archivedate=2008-10-15 |df= }}</ref>
