{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}
'''Sir Olaf Kirkpatrick Kruuse Caroe''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|KCSI|KCIE}} (15 November 1892 – 23 November 1981) was an administrator in [[British India]], working for the [[Indian Civil Service]] and the [[Indian Political Service]].  He served as the Governor of the [[North-West Frontier Province (1901–1955)|North-West Frontier Province]]. He was a strategist of the [[Great Game]] and the [[Cold War]] on the southern periphery of the Soviet Union. His ideas are believed to have been highly influential in shaping the post-War policies of Britain and the United States.

== Early life ==
Olaf Caroe was the son of architect [[William Douglas Caroe]] and Grace Desborough Rendall. He was educated at [[Winchester College]] and [[Magdalen College, Oxford]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Personal recollections of Sir Olaf Caroe |url=http://archiveshub.ac.uk/data/gb206-liddlecollectionind08 |publisher=university of Leeds Special Collections |accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> where he read classics. He served in the army in the [[Punjab region|Punjab]] in [[World War I]], and joined the [[Indian Civil Service]] in 1919.{{sfn|Brobst, The Future of the Great Game|2005|p=xvi}}

==Career==
Caroe subsequently move to the [[Indian Political Service]], where he was influential in foreign policy. He served as the Foreign Secretary to the Government of India through the [[World War II]]. After the war, he was appointed as the Governor of the [[North-West Frontier Province (1901–1955)|North-West Frontier Province]] (NWFP), on the northwest border of the Indian subcontinent, adjoining Afghanistan and Russia.{{sfn|Brobst, Kashmir 1947|1998|p=93}}

Caroe served as the Governor of the NWFP from 1946 to just before the [[Partition of India]] in 1947. Subject to accusations that he was too close to the [[All-India Muslim League|Muslim League]],<ref>{{citation |title=Facts are sacred |chapter=Chapter 18: Mountbatten Gets to Work |first=Khan Abdul |last=Wali Khan |publisher=Awami National Party |chapter-url=http://www.anp.org.pk/factsAreSacredchapter18.htm  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040718075021/http://www.anp.org.pk/factsAreSacredchapter18.htm |archive-date=18 July 2004}}</ref> he encountered opposition from [[Indian National Congress|Congress Party]] politicians,<ref>Parshotam Mehra, [http://www.tribuneindia.com/2001/20011202/spectrum/book4.htm The force Badshah Khan built (review of ''The Pathan Unarmed: Opposition & Memory in the North West Frontier'' by Mukulika Banerjee)],  Tribune India 2 December 2001</ref> and was replaced in mid-1947 by [[Rob Lockhart]] as governor.

== Strategist ==
After returning from India in 1947, he wrote extensively. His strategic ideas proved influential:

{{cquote|At about this time there were those in Washington, looking for ways to secure the oil resources and practice containment in the middle east. The formulations of Sir Olaf Caroe attracted attention and soon found favour in official circles. His article in the March 1949 number of ''Round Table'' and his 1951 book, ''Wells of Power'', led to invitations from the state and defence departments to visit Washington.<ref>
{{citation |last1=Rudolph |first1=Lloyd I. |last2=Rudolph |first2=Susanne Hoeber |title=The Making of US Foreign Policy for South Asia |journal=[[Economic and Political Weekly]] |date=25 February 2006 |pp=703–709
|url=http://political-science.uchicago.edu/faculty/rudolphs/us-asia.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904130237/https://political-science.uchicago.edu/faculty/rudolphs/us-asia.pdf |archive-date=4 September 2006}}</ref>}}

